msContents.summary: Critique of learning, divided into the disciplines of grammar, rhetoric, geometry, arithmetic, astrology, music, logic, physics, and ethics. A short work titled Dialexeis or Dissoi logoi, which was often attributed to Sextus Empiricus and included in manuscripts of his work, is at the end of the volume.

supportDesc.extent: 269 leaves : 162 x 106 (112 x 72) mm. bound to 170 x 112 mm

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 27 long lines; ruled in drypoint with vertical bounding lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in Greek minuscule script by Isidore of Kiev.

decoDesc.decoNote: 4-line initials at the beginning of sections in pale red ink; rubrics and headings in pale red ink.

origin.p: Written in Italy, probably Ferrara, Florence, or Rome, during Isidore's participation in the Council of Florence, 1438-1445.

history.provenance: Probably entered the Vatican Library with a collection of Isidore's papers and books, Vat. Lat. 3951 (as recorded in inventories up to 1518 and not thereafter; probably taken during the sack of Rome in 1527).

Formerly owned by Nicholai von Bodeck of Danzig, 1652 or 1657 (inscription on lost front flyleaf, documented by Hermann Mutschmann, "Die Überlieferung der Schriften der Sextus Empiricus," Hermes 64 (1909), p. 281).
Sold by Sam Fogg Ltd. (London) to Lawrence J. Schoenberg, May 2000.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2012.
